The Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There's a theory that this boson is involved in the mechanism that's responsible for all the matter in the universe.
And then there's the last particle that the Standard Model predicts -- our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but that has not been empirically observed.
But there's still no certainty among physicists that it's the Higgs boson.
There's no doubt that we have a completely new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the Standard Model.
New data released this week at the major physics congress in Kyoto is more like a confirmation, but we still don't have all the data to be absolutely sure.
However, let's assume it's the Higgs boson, since the risk of error seems small, and let's see what it actually is.
There is an undeniable law in this world that no two things can happen at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, or you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
He further divides the physical particles into two categories.
On one side, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow Pauli's principle.
And at the other end of the spectrum are bosons, mean anarchists who don't value anything -- certainly not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups by the device (which is absolutely amazing, by the way) called The Particle Adventure, at Berkeley Labs: mesons, which we'll leave out of the picture here, and "force particles", which are the forces of nature that are spreading and with which the Higgs boson is probably related in some way.
But it has to be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you're reading this, it's because of a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is a "carrier" of the electromagnetic force.
When charged particles accelerate or change direction, they "disrupt" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the bosons, the "carriers of the force".
More stable field
It's the same with the Higgs boson, except that you have to "disrupt" another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; it needs to be excited at very high energy levels, much like the frozen surface of a pond, which is just a very large boulder yesterday.
For this reason, it is necessary to use a particle accelerator as huge as the one at CERN - a large hadron accelerator with a cluster of clusters is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to clarify the relationship between the Higgs boson and matter.
Not all particles or all materials react with an electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself apart on a refrigerator.
And also, not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do have some mass, while others (like the photon, let's look at it) don't.
And Mrs. Novak asks, what is all this research for, what will it "bring us"?
From a scientific point of view, it is a validation of the Standard Model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancy between observations and SM predictions.
And a lot of physicists literally wish they could find them, because the slightest difference could open up space for "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It must be noted that the model still has huge flaws, providing no explanation for gravity (wow!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe's mass (wow!)
But CERN has not yet discovered such contradictions.
Reactions
The impact of these findings on Mr. and Mrs. Novak's daily lives is difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
See, in the very early 1960s, the laser pioneers at Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work would spark.
They're supposed to have scientific applications, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle -- who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first stationary laser beam (the previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I've already said that -- the laser was initially considered a "laboratory toy".
Just think about it.
And, moreover, applications can also come from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle invented a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, though not at all what Boyle originally planned, now serves as the eye of all the digital cameras in the world, and it won him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
Of course, that doesn't mean that the activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that you never really know...
