It's done by solving a mathematical problem for the computers, whose solver, a sort of temporary central banker, will have the right to add this extra line.
This is the process of cutting a file; that is, transforming a huge file into a smaller, unique digital print.
The computers will take over this new transaction and add a number to it, only to then cut the whole thing up.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (many zeroes at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes can easily check it for correctness.
The transaction will then be displayed indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would alter the imprint.
If a user wants to pay twice with the same amount of money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes) for fraud purposes, the network will only confirm one of the two transactions - the other will be omitted because each has a different print.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is divided regularly into two, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but they can be divided up to a hundred millionth, so the margin space is...
The difficulty of the task also increases with increasing computation.
The network has had its ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were hacked and the stored bitcoins were stolen.
"The loophole used is not the protocol itself", says Pierre Noizat, founder of Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also monitors the potential for money laundering through this anonymous service.
But this problem applies to cash as well.
Major players like Wikipedia are rejecting gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, are embracing them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron at the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the current account ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoin is not in circulation.
In November, the "giant discounts" were introduced.
"Thirty thousand dollars was exchanged", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, a bitcoin-to-gold exchange.
Pierre Noizat, who also wrote a textbook on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions, which makes it cheaper.
In addition, the wearer manages his identity and can remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up at retailers where no new terminals or software need to be installed.
All it takes is a phone number, which can be "photographed and recognized", says Pierre Noizat, who says he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems and move towards more horizontal systems.
"It will be a while before Bitcoin takes hold, but 2013 could be a defining year", he predicts.
In addition, the ECB's report envisages a reassessment of the various risks currently considered to be elevated if this type of money is to succeed.
