Difficult Work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Morsi has embarked on another round of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided country in its history over the promulgation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, he has chosen to play the bait.
On Wednesday, he announced that, regardless of the opinion of everyone else, the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly two more months to complete the necessary work.
Egypt has been using the interim text for almost two years, which has been amended many times, weakening the country's constitutional stability and leading to legal wrangling.
This new initiative has only further divided the country.
In the opposition's view, the president persists in his "autocratic delusion", continues to "break his word" and "trample on the law".
However, its supporters say it is a means to quickly resolve the constitutional and political crisis and speed up the transition process.
A referendum is due in two weeks.
It's a very short time frame that will force the Brotherhood to back down from its intention to clarify text to Egyptians article by article.
For the president, it's also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy while the country is rocked by protests.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote yes.
Especially because this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: "Either you approve my text or I will keep unlimited powers", which would otherwise end when the new constitution is approved.
And in this particular atmosphere, yesterday 85 members of the aforementioned constituent assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most of the liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the Constitution was promulgated, they knocked on doors, saying they had no way to assert their views.
Human rights advocates, civil society, and members of religious minorities have followed suit.
To achieve tolerability, 11 people were hastily added to the replacement ranks yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators also commented that one of the few disputes that day revolved around the... prayer clock, with some committee members holding the view that the clocks in the boardroom were not set correctly.
The text voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term "principle" with the term "rule", allowing for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article was not corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", argue liberals, who see it as a rhetorical problem.
They say the Islamization of the constitution is done through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which confers on al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular on issues of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egyptologist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "those who speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This is the beginning of the theocracy".
The liberals' concerns are further fueled by the fact that the next university president should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, no specific religious consequences have been seen.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a largely civilian state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulama but university workers, many of them graduated from French schools", mildly worries Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on Egypt's constitutional transition.
However, he agrees that "there may be differences in the interpretation of Article 220 because the terms used are religious.
There is a reference to fiqh in particular.
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on this".
The text approved yesterday is being heavily criticized for its religious aspects and the expanded powers it grants to the president of the republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant reduction in their numbers compared to the previous regime.
Another contentious location: the powers vested in the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the military officials, the audit of the defence budget will not be carried out by Parliament but by the National Defence Council.
Furthermore, the trial of civilians in military courts will not be prohibited, as the association for the protection of human rights has demanded.
The association expresses its doubts about the text, which they consider to be against freedom.
The criminal act of blasphemy is maintained and insult remains prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article addresses the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
The only positive point, she said, was the prohibition on torture in Article 36.
That word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to make a televised speech last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are awaiting holy sites, the belly of the world, and a sea of saturated salt solution
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of Bible truths, modern conveniences, and the untouched nature.
AaF has identified the top five reasons why you should visit Israel.
Bow down to holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is claimed that all who enter this "bath" will be subjected to divine mercy.
And Galilee - the site of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming a storm, and filling his nets.
There, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples and after his resurrection.
But the most holy place is in Jerusalem.
Here, believers will walk the Way of Sorrow, or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It starts at the Antonia Fort - Pretoria - where the trial was held, runs through the streets of the Old City, and leads to the Temple of God's Tomb on Golgotha - the place of the crucifixion, the anointing stone, and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew from which they made the cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for Jews - the Western Wall, a remnant of the temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
Traditionally, people of various faiths leave wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take the path vertically
The ruins of Masada's fortress are the remains of a secret refuge from the enemy that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 B.C.E.
The wreckage is located on a cliff in the mountains at an altitude of 450 meters above sea level.
Only those who are involved in mountaineering can get to it by themselves.
The rest will be taken to this historic mountain by cable car.
And in the north, at an altitude of 1,600 to 2,040 meters [1,600-2040 ft], is the famous ski resort of Hermon, which experiences a huge influx of tourists during the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists to this ski paradise from the bottom of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, the pagan gods lived on top of the mountain.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting ones, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains the ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in caves in the Judean Desert, as well as some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
His paintings are widely represented in the exhibition by the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Acre, you can visit the Al Basha Baths Museum, which showcases several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with statues of bath users and bath attendants from the time.
In Caesarea, the unique private Ralli Museum is worth a visit, where you can admire the sculptures of Dalí and Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly declined.
The fifth museum - the Holocaust Museum, or Yad Vashem, in Tel Aviv - tells the story of one of history's most dramatic pages.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk in, and you're in complete darkness.
The stars are shining.
And they're the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries where they died.
Ukraine is also listed.
Improving Your Health
Israel's three main spa resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red, and Dead Seas.
Each of these has swimming pools, water parks, a dolphinarium, and an oceanarium.
Interestingly, bathing in the Red Sea is possible even during the winter months, since the water temperature in the Red Sea stays at about 70 degrees Fahrenheit [21°C] and the air warms up to 90 degrees Fahrenheit [23°C].
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
The Dead Sea is, by the way, the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest point on the planet's landmass - at 417 meters below sea level.
The azure water is a saturated salt solution that easily keeps even people who cannot swim afloat.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo a treatment using salt water, saltpeter, and medicinal mud that can treat medical problems like dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to cure your broken nerves.
Touch the mysterious past of the ancient world
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the small town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
They were the famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia.
Mentions of this city are found in the earliest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it's where Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists do love wandering through narrow alleys named after the signs of the zodiac.
They say if you press against the wall in the alley of your sign, luck will favor you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to have their picture taken.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the Crusader fortress.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully renovated theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, a word
If you are going to Israel, you need not worry about your imperfect English: about 30% of the population in this country speaks Russian.
It is better to take cash with you, not in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily exchanged for shekels (now about $1.00).
Buses are the main means of transportation in Jerusalem, but there is a high-speed tram system in Jerusalem, and the city of Haifa has the only subway line in the country with six stations, connecting the lower city to the upper city.
It's basically an underground cable car.
All forms of public transport cost six shekels, which is a one-and-a-half-hour drive.
In Israel, the Sabbath is observed on the Sabbath day according to Jewish tradition.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops, and public transportation are closed.
And Sunday morning is the start of the work week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, you will only get kosher food: with the exception of pork, seafood, fish without skin and foods containing a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a wide variety of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts made from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, various kinds of sauces, ground chickpeas - falafel, fruit, and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are plenty of weaned cats who gracefully "wander about as they please".
In the evening, you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The front cats love crowded places and will gladly indulge in any good.
Renting a car will cost from $37 a day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 a day (Audi A6, Volvo S80), depending on the brand.
Plus the insurance - $15 a day.
And borrowing a bike will cost about 15 shekels a day.
Museum tickets are 30 shekels on average.
Expressed in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
The largest number of visitors came from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, and Ukraine.
The Promised Land was visited by 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the visa abolition of 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" announces to Moscow: emigrants save money on language
While lawmakers and human rights defenders are still debating the law on compulsory language exams, fraudsters have already appeared in the country selling "fake" certificates
Each year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn enough money to support their families at home.
On December 1, a law came into force that will require every migrant worker to pass a Russian language test.
So far, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the services, housing, public utilities, lifestyle and retail sectors.
However, the FMS promises that in time, the appropriate tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the basics of law.
Language skills will also be required for obtaining and renewing a work permit.
The exemption applies only to nationals of countries where Russian is the official language.
The law also exempts people who successfully passed the certification and obtained an academic diploma before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Benefit, condemnation and protection of rights
The network of test sites will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; more than 160 such centers are already in operation in Russia.
The initiative to promote the introduction of testing was also supported by the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service (FMS).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders were able to ask the question in the press many times: what will it really do?
What will change the requirement to know the language for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
First of all, migration officials say, it will reduce the number of people who suffer from "slave labor".
Many people today talk about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, chairman of the board of FMS Russia in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights should be started before their departure.
Only an organised recruitment system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for immigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language, says Sebelev, the future migrant is doomed to encounter dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "pass" to a terrible, cramped shelter where he and dozens of others like him will starve for months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We've been getting a lot of complaints from our migrant workers.
"They promise them one thing in their homeland, but when they arrive they cheat them, confiscate their passports, do not pay the wages promised", says Tolib Sharipov, head of Tajikistan's main labour migration administration.
Don't give me that!
Especially since many citizens of Central Asian republics who intend to go to Russia to work admit that they not only do not know the language of the country to which they want to go but have no experience even in the work at hand.
Of course, it is not their fault, but rather a misfortune: very few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least a decent basic education.
After all, their families also need to feed their children, not to mention clothe, shoe, and school them properly.
As children grow into working age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language, it's difficult, they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior".
It is true that human rights defenders point out one important point regarding the language test law.
The testing will only be done on those migrants who have legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't pass their exams or get any other official job.
Meanwhile, most migrant workers are still living in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized Entry is Not Allowed"
Many of the new workers say that it is not easy to get official status in our country.
The reason is, there's all these bureaucratic hurdles and all these language difficulties.
And legalization costs money, from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake license plate can be obtained quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
Russian police officers know that we have essentially fake documents, no registration, and that leads to cases of blackmail.
"They charge a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea", Umed Chushkadamov, a Tajik citizen, told reporters about his experience.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the language law, it was found that not only immigrants' registration documents were being falsified.
FMS staff have already seized several false certificates of passing a language test.
The forged documents are printed on a regular color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get them for free: each of the migrants paid 7,000 rubles for the document in the hope of easing their test passing problems.
This is two and a half times the amount of passing the official test: it will cost migrant workers 3,000 rubles.
The main task for the near future is to secure the system from corruption so that workers cannot easily buy documents, government officials and human rights advocates agree.
Government authorities can promise foreign workers who fail the tests the first time enough time to complete a basic Russian language course.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active interaction with people is not required.
