In simple terms, European legislation governs how public procurement is handled, followed by national legislation and then by practice.
We have put all this together and although the control is not yet complete, we have found very interesting differences - in general terms, the legislation is perhaps "strict and more perfect" here, but the practice itself is better in Germany in some respects.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to create ever more precise rules, but that the application of the law itself needs to be addressed.
