Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency at a meeting of ESA ministers, the second former Eastern bloc country (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and has participated in a number of ESA projects over the years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already interested in space flights before World War II; but they were not always understood.
I recall, for example, the lecture given by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6, 1933, presenting ideas from his pioneering work Introduction to Astronautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and years later Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 he received the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his entry into space in France.
The late Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and space exploration.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of space exploration, and his contribution was recognized by the naming of a crater on the far side of the moon after him.
As early as 1925, a railway drainage system was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the design is unknown and the details of the project are not known.
It's also unclear if the missile was intended to launch the drezin or to slow it down.
Information about this drezin is only known from the contemporary press.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to use rocket-propelled grenades.
The research was carried out by the Armament Technology Cell in collaboration with Prof. Mieczysław Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzycki.
From the surviving materials, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, the arrival of the German troops interrupted the research.
In 1937, a photoelectric fighter rocket designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work Rakiet - torpedo powietrzna and rakietobomba lotnicza by Leliwy-Krzywobloky was published.
Both projects were designed for military use with rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were devoted to the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities were terminated by the outbreak of war.
Further works on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of the company is in the November 1954 issue of Problems magazine, which features four more extensive articles on astronautics.
One of them, by Professor M. Subotowicze, proposes the creation of a company that will deal with space.
By that time, satellite projects were well under way, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn the PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959) became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, PTA played a significant role in the development of the highly successful RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, with a range of 1,800 meters, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of the RM-2 two-stage rocket were started in the Bled desert.
The rocket was four feet long and weighed about 11 pounds.
The next development type was already capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to track high winds.
However, in 1962 further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RMs was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and a launch weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) which differed in the size of space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A had a space of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1B had a space of 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C had a space of 0.62 litres.
Maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aviation, with first flight tests beginning in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a takeoff weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
