Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circuses
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually publishes a survey on the most absurd bank fee, has now decided to launch a competition on the "most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop".
"We were led to this by the recent event when the EU is planning to adopt a 40% quota for women in the leadership of large European companies", said Patrik Nacher, the organiser of the survey.
Among the absurdities mentioned is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify the rates of insurance for men and women.
Until now, women have been given a premium in life insurance prices because they are objectively less risky for insurance companies.
"More incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of the year.
The vote itself will then take place until the end of February 2013", Nacher informed.
Controversial EU regulations include a mandatory blending of biofuels, which is damaging to the environment, a ban on reliable mercury thermometers, which contain relatively few dangerous substances, and a directive on the size of chicken cages, which has led to a significant increase in the price of eggs this year.
Criticism has also previously been directed at the de facto ban on the use of the term 'butter' or the withdrawal of traditional light bulbs from sale.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters long
The EU apparatus often decides under pressure from a business or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by a state or group of states (the Czech Republic now even enforces the demands of its banks by veto).
The lobby also argued that, for example, the highest quality bananas in the Union had to be at least 14 cm long and not have to show 'anomalous curvature'.
The European Commission has defended itself by simply harmonising the previously inconsistent national standards that had complicated trade.
The EU has already softened the rules on fruit and vegetables, despite opposition from some countries, pointing out that existing directives lead to food waste.
The EU regulation last year that inflatable balloons must be labelled with a warning that children under 8 years of age must not inflate without adult supervision is also a candidate to win the poll.
The EU has cited US research showing that balloons between toys are the leading cause of death from asphyxiation in children.
Similar restrictions now apply to children under 14 when blowing on parade jackets.
Curious ideas are born at home
The rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd - anyone who holds any official position in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia, given the sensitivity of the subject for Greece, and must speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia) instead.
The Banking fees.com server, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, nominated the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a Member State as one of the absurdities mentioned above.
The EU has set maximum quantities of food stocks that could be in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the Union.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the prescribed volumes for preserved mushrooms, for which it faced a high fine.
The survey organizers were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea and the idea of granting grants to applicants for a grant.
These ideas, however, did not originate in Brussels, but in Prague.
"We are handicapped by not having the sea.
We will ask the European Union for a refund", said Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD), then Minister of Agriculture, in the autumn of 2004.
He argued that we had a lot of grain and that the so-called intervention purchases meant that the warehouses were full and he had to export them.
The EU should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros to keep the Czech Republic close to ports, according to Palas.
The European Commission finally accommodated the Czech Republic by holding a tender to buy grain from countries without access to the sea.
The subsidy was offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development, headed by Minister Pavel German (US-DEU), specifically to prepare applications for the grant from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
While regulations in the Member States are easily criticised, many experts say that the EU's efforts to regulate and at the same time to make the whole Union work and develop more efficiently deserve recognition.
A more serious problem, experts say, is the use of EU grants for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration but which have been forced on themselves by the Member States in budgetary negotiations.
The Czech people are also excited by the fact that, like other EU countries, the Czech Republic is fighting in Brussels for the right to specifically label its traditional products, and is not always successful in this battle.
Although the Czechs defended the name Olomouc after a six-year war with the Germans and Austrians, our local rum, whose tradition dates back to the 19th century, had to be renamed local.
Only products from cane distillate, not sugar beet, may bear the name rum.
The official EU list of registered products already includes world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from Lübeck, Germany, and Parma ham, such as Karlovy Vary dry sausages, Pohořelecký and Tréboň carp and hops.
The EU trade mark can also be used for Pardubice pipes and fire pipes.
People want me to save the Republic, but I'm an amateur, says Okamura
Senator, how does a person think he wants to run for president?
I'm not trying to be a senator or a president.
If our country was running smoothly, I wouldn't be running.
But I can't stand to see the country robbed for the last 20 years, with thieves running around, people raising taxes and retirement ages.
I had no ambition to be a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, I try to come up with a solution to change it.
And since I'm already 40 and an independent, I have no choice but to run for senator or president.
You made it to the Senate, but you soon left for the Castle.
Doesn't that turn your back on the people who elected you?
I've said all along that I'd go to the battle for Castle based on the Senate election results.
I later made it clear that if I was elected senator, I would run for president.
But my goal is not function, function is a tool to make my vision a reality.
That's why I need the greatest possible influence and the strongest possible mandate.
The problem is, not only do we as a nation swear in pubs and on TV, but we trample on anyone who tries to make a difference.
Add to that the media that dehumanizes man and confuses freedom of speech with freedom to lie.
I was accused of bribing journalists or being an adviser to George Paroubek.
Let's get to your visions.
You went into the fight for the castle with a thesis of material and criminal liability of politicians and back confessions of property over 20 million.
You'll have to change the law to do that.
But as president, you don't have that authority, and only the Senate as a whole can make laws.
How do you want to handle this?
When I lobbied as a citizen to make guiding a free profession, it was passed.
The problem is politics -- when someone comes up with a good proposal from the left or the right, they deliberately reject it, and that holds the citizens back.
As an independent, I have a much greater potential to win support from all the parties in Parliament.
My advantage is that without partisan boxing and dogma, I can take what's best for our country from every side and apply it.
Do you prefer to be on the right or the left?
From a Czech point of view, I think people rank me more to the left.
It doesn't matter to me if it's a little to the left or a little to the right.
It's important to me that we move forward.
I don't care if someone's on the left or the right, I want to bring people together.
I will always support any publicly good solution, even if it is proposed by the KSČM or ODS, and I will also be against a bad idea.
You're happy when someone calls you a populist.
But you don't prove it by what you said?
When you create a business plan for a company, you also have some ideal goal and vision.
And that's what you're getting close to.
Some might call it populism, but all of the proposals I'm talking about are already working in the world, or have been talked about by leading experts.
But without the support of Parliament, you'll be left with only passwords.
And that's not gonna do you any good in politics in the long run.
Or do you think that by going out and talking to people, you're going to be able to enforce, say, criminal and property liability?
I have no other choice.
To persuade politicians, journalists and the public to try and get on our side to make it happen.
If I were elected president, I would have no problem hosting a live television broadcast where I would ask the chairmen of parliamentary parties to legislate corporal and criminal liability for politicians, officials, judges and prosecutors.
And they might have to tell you why they don't want it.
If you have a strong personality who can name the bad guys, you can push the political scene.
Take the direct election of the president, it was a public pressure.
I'm being honest, I'm an amateur, I'm not a genius or an intellectual.
I'm trying to find allies for my views and vision.
I'm just getting started in politics and I'm trying to get a majority for my program.
I'm trying to move things along on my own, and if I don't, I'm gonna quit in six years and go back to the private sector.
Sounds a little like Okamura's supposed to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know I can't do anything in one person, so I've been going around to a lot of famous people to see if they'd run for the Senate, too.
I went to see Radim Yanchura, he refused because of the amount of work.
At least I supported investigative journalist Jan Lorenca, who was exposing the light fuel oil scams.
I ran with the idea that people were really unhappy, but now I'm on the draught.
Sixty percent of the people didn't vote, and those who did mostly voted for the establishment.
We're the only two independents in the Senate.
The people have manipulated the Senate to make it difficult to enforce the changes.
I will still fight for my vision, like direct election of mayors or captains.
Are you thinking of starting your own party?
I haven't considered it yet because I don't have time to go through the clean history of every potential party, and I don't have the money to do that.
I don't even have money for the presidential campaign, I only have 20 grand in my transparent account.
You don't have any money?
Speaking of property claims, what's yours?
Private property, I'd estimate at about 60 million.
I have a property in Prague for about 25 million, an apartment for 10 million, another apartment for 8 million, a collection of art for about 10 million, an Aston Martin for 3.5 million and a Škoda Superb for a million and then I have a couple of million in the account.
By the way, the reason I got the Aston Martin is because it was my boyhood dream - I always liked James Bond, who drove a car, was gallant with women and at the same time fought against evil and bad.
You drive an Aston Martin, you own $60 million in assets, and you don't have campaign funds?
You say you want to change the republic, but you don't want to put much money into it.
That's not very convincing.
I don't have 15 million dollars for the campaign.
You want me to go into debt?
I've already put 2.5 million into the campaign.
The fact that I don't have any sponsors suggests that my program probably isn't that popular.
And I don't have to pay for my campaign.
My campaign expenses will basically be covered by what I'm getting as a senator.
But I wouldn't be able to make a living from it, for example, I couldn't afford to pay for my son's English school, which costs 30,000 a month.
If I was just trying to make money, I wouldn't be running.
So you're going to keep doing business to make a living?
Didn't you say you'd suppress these activities?
