The architects of MVRDV are proof that real adventures don't just happen in the head - for example, Spijkenisse and the recently built Mountain of Books - 2 pictures
"The building looks cheerful, futuristic, and finally something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, walking alongside.
Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a nearby large company, says, "Of course, the house is nice".
But I ask, why do we need a library today?
Everybody has the Internet, iPads and e-books.
None of these old-fashioned libraries are voluntarily open anymore, are they?
Spijkenisse, a settlement just outside Rotterdam with no work opportunities of its own, not even worth visiting, holds a remarkable record.
This municipality of 80 000 inhabitants has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
To remedy this stupid situation, a few years ago a decision was made to contribute to general education by building seven beautifully painted iron-concrete miniature fictional bridges, as depicted on euro banknotes.
The success of the education offensive was not dizzying.
And so the city councilmen realized that there was only one way to become masters of statistics: we had to have a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural studio MVRDV, master of wildly daring column graphs and maker of funny, often even cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual calm and showed up at the 2003 competition with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the committee was still looking around in amazement and shrugging their shoulders, the insolent Maas stacked his gifts on top of each other in order of size and ended his activist-led speech with the words "Dear City People!"
So this is my proposal for the Book Mountain in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was topped at a cost of 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project which also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and townhouses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, Mountain of Books was awarded second place in the "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
A small-town gray area that until now has been unable to offer more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unusually ugly town hall, behind the white facade of which you would expect a dairy, is now enriched by a bit of contemporary architecture.
Above all, however, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
It 's a long way to the book .
First impression: a reading eldorado under the cheese cover.
Although there is an elevator through the mountain, you will discover true spatial and reading passion only by walking over the topography.
The glass interior is bright and transparent on all sides, the floor of the burnt-out cabin and the elegant street lamps clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, and a dog and boys and girls playing football.
And books everywhere, books, books.
"Normally, bookshelves line the facade, and in the middle is a large dark space that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
We've built the classic space configuration upside down and we've stretched the space for the readers from the inside out.
The interior of the Mountain of Books is well-used: the center houses offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a home appliance center.
A special treat is the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall paneling, sometimes a window sill, and sometimes a stairway railing.
The look, texture and smell are alien.
Even the most accomplished architects and civil engineers are shaking their heads over unknown building materials.
"We wanted to work here with recycled materials", says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the Municipality of Spijkenisse, when asked by the Standard magazine.
So one day, at a farm in Frisco, we came across a suitable agricultural waste product.
Millimeter-sized synthetic rune has been used for many years as a rootstock in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It's cheap and time-efficient.
Thin fabric lasts one or two seasons and then it's ripe to be thrown away in bulk.
For the library, the rune was cut into four-centimeter-thick plates - the first time it had been cut in such quantity.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (LBP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and load-bearing material that smells a little like a new car and a little like sports shoes.
You take 105 steps to the top.
At the end of the nearly 500-meter trek, you will be rewarded in the literary café with not only a fantastic view of the city but also Dutch croquettes and figs in flower pots.
They take care of the atmosphere, but most importantly the right humidity in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a new soul
"You might not believe it, but despite the many glass panes, this house is an example of ecological design", says Trouborst.
It heats and cools with the earth's heat.
Although the Mountain of Books is under a glass lid, the sun shines in only briefly, even on sunny days.
Wide wooden bars, perpendicular to the glass facade, act as shade and absorb much of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest will be handled by fully automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, a beginner skeptic in the IT industry, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there.
And also a teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde, whom Boekenberg even refers to as the "long-awaited soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason: every resident of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate one book from their personal fund.
The first step was to fill the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library, which now numbers 70,000 items.
The concept worked.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that our invitation has now given each resident a certain relationship to the new house.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it was just for decoration.
That's what MVRDV has done in the royal discipline of what's called, in professional parlance, identity formation.
Spijkenisse was writing the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated he is.
It's ultimately the starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to US-European relations expert Stephen Szabo, this puts Berlin on a narrow diplomatic edge.
Deutsche Welle: Germany first signaled earlier this week that it would vote against a proposal for observer status for the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, of course, Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think they'll support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the no-fly zone.
It was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stand on important international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason is that they are changing their foreign policy, from a policy that was, so to speak, controlled by the United States, to a German foreign policy.
The situation is made more difficult by the lack of coherent and unified policies in Europe.
So the Germans are between two fronts.
They're expected to play more independent roles, but they're not used to it.
I think they're just settling into their role, but they're on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
To foreign policy, like they have in France or Britain.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It shows a willingness to take positions that are independent of the positions of the US or European partners when it comes to national interests.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, exports and its relations with certain regions, like Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of other Great Powers and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Did economic interests influence the stance on the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has a large market in the Middle East, particularly in the Persian Gulf countries.
So they have to be careful not to intimidate the public, but also the elites in the Arab countries.
It's a factor, though.
I don't want to overstate the importance of this, but it's not a one-sided relationship.
However, it plays an important role in German thinking.
Did Germany's abstention from voting on both important decisions, such as the Palestine vote, hurt relations between Germany and the United States?
I think there is a great deal of understanding in Europe and even in the United States for the German position.
That's why I don't think it was as dramatic a break as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect from this.
This signals that it must be considered an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has been very clear in its veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration has a secret understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation there, he cannot, of course, take that stand publicly.
I think the differences in opinion really aren't as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not very enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies at all.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the USA on the one hand and its position as the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what's making it hard for the Germans.
It would of course be a little easier for Germany if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not happening at the moment.
So they can't be part of the larger line and they have to push things forward from their own position instead.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take a leading role in the future and push Europe to adopt a European attitude.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, especially with the relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans understand that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player?
Or is the leadership role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult for this country to play a greater role.
If you look at the European crisis, for example, every time Germany takes on a bigger role, there's anti-German sentiment.
That doesn't make it any easier for the Germans.
It's actually an old problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be acceptable to all kinds of neighbors and opinions, and that's not easy.
The US influence in European politics is now steadily declining, but the EU is not currently filling this vacuum.
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to study the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
