Armani is a world-famous brand, and so is Polo Ralph Lauren.
What is an Armani Polo?
Behind this is a trademark that is fully registered in China but has nothing to do with the original company.
However, it shall enjoy protection until it is sued by the actual proprietors of the trade mark.
And even then, it's not clear if they'll get justice.
"It's getting harder and harder for foreigners to protect their brands in China", says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, which specializes in infringements in the Far East.
Every week, a new case lands on my desk.
Forgers need only a few more letters to register their trademarks.
For example, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada, they get registered as Prada-Kny.
German companies, such as the sportswear manufacturer Puma, are also legally copied in this way.
Pattloch opens up the register with the records of the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark, a fake name that also parasitizes on the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
It's well known that the Chinese are the world champions in copy and copy infringement.
In the big cities, there are multi-storey shops, which sell almost exclusively counterfeits.
But Pattloch's case is different, because he's working on behalf of his clients to prevent Chinese companies from getting a fully-official license from the trademark office to use a trademark that's already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Mingpai", the associated brand.
This word focuses on "Bang Dakuan".
That's women who go after rich men.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt.
"It's hurting business, we have to fight it", Pattloch urges.
"The badge is diluted, the exclusive status is gone, the image damage is enormous".
The financial losses and legal costs to the affected industries are in the millions, especially for expensive sample products.
According to data from the market research company CLSA, China is the third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market with a volume of EUR 15 billion per year.
However, the deletion of questionable registrations can be difficult and costly.
The trial could go on for up to nine years with uncertain outcome.
Pattloch recounts cases in which the court rejected lawsuits because the name had become a "market reality" after a long time.
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he still has to pay the plagiarist because he damaged his brand in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes it's the law of the jungle.
The known cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal dispute with the construction machinery manufacturer SANA, a company that had recently acquired the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why the Chinese are still allowed to use the emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Geely, which bought Volvo, originally used a blue-and-white logo that resembled a BMW.
Fashion goods maker Lacoste lost in China to counterfeiters from Hong Kong and Singapore who turned the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt.
