Petronella Wyatt: "I was forced to leave Oxford because I am a conservative".
It's not just college students today who are being attacked for their beliefs.
I can't remember a time when I didn't dream of studying at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother went to what I thought was the world's greatest center of learning, a modern Greek symposium that encouraged the two pillars of civilization, free thought and tolerance.
And yet, in the late 1980s, within two weeks of entering Worcester College, where I was going to study history, I packed my bags and plunged into the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed I gave it up because I objected to making love to students in the next room.
Author A. N. Wilson bluntly stated that I left because I was forced to drink from beaten cups.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was the object of systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my rather bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one reason, and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment, it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a high-ranking adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a Conservative.
You may be wondering why I'm bringing this up now.
Simply because recent reports suggest that a new generation of students on the right of center are suffering similar harassment.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of these students demanded equal rights protection for gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior College Association (JCR) at Corpus Christi College claim that because of their political views, they are "often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks, and made to feel unwelcome".
They're asking for a position on the university's equal opportunity committee to ensure they can express their views freely.
