At other colleges, conservative students say they are being treated as "victims" because of the higher tuition.
Twenty-year-old Luke Black, vice-president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told the Sunday newspaper that "left influence is growing in the universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even meeting us".
Twenty-one-year-old Corpus Christi history student Samuel Roberts, who is behind the more conservative movement, says the climate is "unpleasant", while 19-year-old OUCA president-elect Stephanie Cherill says there has been a deterioration in JCR members' attitude toward people on the right of the center.
"This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion as well as to the well-being of members", he says.
