The toughest craft in the world: sulfur carriers in the Kawah Ijen area
For four euros, the carriers in the Indonesian volcano area risk their lives and health as they carry 70 kilograms of sulfur down steep rocky trails.
There are people for whom their jobs are hell, and there are people who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of 400 miners who earn a living mining sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, they must travel to the bottom of the crater every day, where sulfur gases escape from the Earth's interior and become solid when exposed to air.
After cutting large blocks of sulfur, weighing up to 130 pounds [70 kg], he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
It is only a quarter mile [2,386 m] to the summit of the volcano, but exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to make the tortuous ascent, balancing and carefully considering their steps so as not to slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any stumbling could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell from the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners in Kawah only make five cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
When they are up there, they fight their way past the tourists who take pictures of them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and they carry the heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company has placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining the volcano since 1960, has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since the mineral has its place in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Because we normally carry 70 kilograms [70 lb], we earn about 46,000 rupees [US$3,500] each way", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
