Singapore is looking for a baby to save the economy
Singaporeans blame not having children for their careers, stress, and the cost of living and education.
"Singapore's population needs to grow".
I'm married and I'm a patriot, you're my wife and you're a patriot, so let's fulfill our civic duty and create a new life!
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a menthol candy ad, but despite this - or perhaps because of it - the video went viral on YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
These are the words of a rapper who uses local slang like "put the pussy in the oven" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency that created the video, hopes to bring attention to the problem in a humorous way.
Douglas Hamilton, the agency's artistic director, says that he wanted to use the influence of music to help people fulfill "their civic duty".
"It's all about the Internet, so it had to be fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in this country.
We're the worst in the world at reproducing our population, so we felt like this was a topic we needed to address.
We knew the government was trying a lot of things like spreading pheromone perfumes or hosting dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they were not entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible, like compose a rap, to solve this problem".
1.2 children
The one that doesn't take this too lightly is the Singaporean government.
They spend $1,300 a year encouraging citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and provides financial benefits.
All these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, technologically advanced city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative officials and strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore, given the distribution of population, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded 2, which is considered the recovery rate, was in 1976.
Why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Department of the National Population Bureau, says that this is because of "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
"People have a wider range of choices when it comes to life goals and priorities, not just marriage and family", he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of single people and to the postponement of marriage and childbearing, resulting in a decline in the birth rate in Singapore.
While there were efforts to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as part of immigration policy as a measure to counter population decline, this has caused resentment among locals.
Some Singaporean websites show open xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and making little effort to integrate.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one reason why Singapore's ruling party recorded its worst election result since independence last year.
After the elections, there was an attempt to solve the problem with quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unintended Consequences
While the decline in birth rates has known effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health expenditure and immigration policy, there have also been some unexpected consequences in the case of Singapore.
The government is trying to keep the number of small houses down.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Office of Urban Development has begun to regulate the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that can be built in certain urban areas.
These apartments are 46 square meters and have been very successful in sales.
However, there are concerns that these flats may encourage a youthful lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the developer EL Developers, claims that their "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger houses.
"They are more popular, and they sell out days to weeks faster than larger homes.
So they're much better for our cash flow".
However, it admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules could lead to a rise in the nation's birth rate, interviews with Singaporeans working in the city's downtown financial district suggest they won't have much effect.
"People are always under stress, housing is expensive, and education is expensive, so many people put it off", says a young official.
"Let the rest have children.
But for me, it's important to rely on my own money and time", says another, in his 20's.
Both men and women cite career, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons for not having children.
So no matter how hard the government tries to force people to have children, it is Singaporeans who ultimately have the final say in family planning.
What's private offline is private online.
It's private.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something personal or "the area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any interference".
What is privacy for someone under 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the danger of posting things on the Internet that he would most likely not tell anyone in normal communication?
ElPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be 'something entirely their own' at a personal level and 'username and password' when it came to social networks.
"My biggest secret is not to be told", says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the importance of privacy on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
