"I put nice pictures on FB or pictures of us playing.
I also talk to people I know.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or a photo that made someone laugh", he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to post obscene photos, photographs of naked people or photographs of crimes, or to write degrading or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 of his Facebook friends and his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password to one of the accounts.
"I started a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there", he adds.
"Social networking is fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends", she says.
He says without hesitation that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
He wouldn't even care if someone referred him to someone he didn't know.
Fourteen-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, MySpace, and Ask, and on the latter, he admits that he does not know 20 people on his friend list.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music", he says.
According to this boy, none of them ever told him anything, asked for his address or phone number.
"If they press me or demand that I do it, I simply delete them from my account", she admits.
Jose signed up for Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
These boys are no strangers to what is now called cyberbullying.
"A well-known friend was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who it was", he confirms.
According to Jose, the victim never logged out of the account.
"You just activated private mode".
Then it explains a series of steps to set up the account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this guy would post pictures of people he knows in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if I was in trouble or just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying", he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate student in Education, believes that for children and teens to navigate social media well, they need to understand that the main purpose of social media is to inform.
He says: "The Internet began as a means of finding information, but the advent of social media changed the rules of the game".
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate student in education at Yale University and author of Digital Aborigines and Digital Immigrants, introduced these terms to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born in this technology era.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and we are learning ourselves", he says.
He explains that it is a difficult subject "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to spread, publish and say and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ready for it".
Also, to be considerate of others at a time when their greatest desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends, and not to think about the consequences".
She says that the most effective way to teach children and teenagers about privacy is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work", he adds.
Marrielos Porras goes on to list some options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or, "Would you like someone to post your picture the way you posted your friend's?"
Do you know what other people are saying about you?
When you tag people in party photos, did you ask those people for permission?
And one more thing: Does everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to make them realize that they have to behave in an online environment as well as offline.
It's the same rules.
"Offline, respect, morality and other principles govern a person, and the same should apply to social media", he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a primary school teacher, and an educational consultant, explains that it is essential for parents to read carefully the rules of social networking.
"If they understand the insidiousness of each one, they have a good basis for discussing the consequences of setting up an Internet account with their children.
For example, about age or what is allowed to share or publish", he says.
Guardia feels that it is important to remind children of the traditional rule "don't talk to strangers".
The South American Summit ends and the Lima Declaration is not published.
The sixth summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Peru ended today without the issuance of the Lima Declaration, which was announced and reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the sixth UNASUR summit, but officials from the Foreign Ministry and the presidential office, who initially said they would release the document after the summit, said it would be posted later on the Peruvian government's website.
They further stated that the content was made public by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Journalists were restricted in their access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential meeting was broadcast in the press room without sound with the message "confidential meeting, audio transmission blocked".
The limited information available to journalists was provided by the press representatives of some governments present, but not by the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the meeting was a list of the presidents participating, which provoked the anger of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent out an email to the media with a "concluding statement" from the summit, but it was only a statement by President Humala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA), and even then the Lima Declaration, originally promised, was not published, despite press calls.
The official website of ASPA says that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure broadcasts for all journalists, but completely prevented the flow of information.
The Summit concluded, inter alia, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to the adoption of the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
Peruvian President Ollanta Humala and Chilean President Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin hearing defense testimony from both sides on Monday to address the dispute that Lima launched against Santiago.
"We will submit and execute the judgment that resolves the dispute that we are hearing today in this international court", said President Humala along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of disputes, conventions and international courts", Piñera added, greeting President Humalu with a handshake of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents to submit to the International Court of Justice's ruling came after Colombia this week adopted the Bogota Pact, expressing its submission to the rulings of the international court that ruled on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which Colombia considered to be entirely flawed.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chavez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 after the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was given the task of opening the morning's speeches and closing the Lima summit shortly after noon.
The President read the final document, which announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects were planned between the South American countries, with investments totaling $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the member countries of UNASUR would take 'important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which residence agreements are being extended'.
He said that actions were being supported to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil unrest and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and cheap internet in all parts of South America, and to jointly and effectively respond to the risks of natural disasters".
When Europe is in crisis, "economic consolidation [in Latin America] should not be a victorious force, but should serve to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future", Humala added.
"We have decided to prioritise a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport connectivity in different parts of South America, especially rural and border areas... to better connect our countries and create new economic ties", the Peruvian president said in a speech read out.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and its trans-boundary axes from the coast to Brazil, and two others concern better connectivity with Ecuador, but did not elaborate.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return her to the Union of South American Nations", from which she is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted at the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region, one that is integrated and has good neighbourly relations.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to discuss respectfully the International Court of Justice's ruling on the maritime border dispute disputed by Bogotá.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)", Santos said.
'We will discuss all solutions, none excluded, including a treaty with Nicaragua that requires negotiations with that country,' he stressed.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega to conduct the negotiations in the most civilized and considerate way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City to attend the inauguration of President Enrique Peñi Nieta.
The Summit held a preliminary meeting of Union Defence Ministers to adopt an Action Plan for 2013 to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
The members of UNASUR are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru is the interim chair of this regional bloc.
Rafael Correa: South America must learn from Europe on integration
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa announced today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which "South America, in this case, really, must learn from Europe".
Correa, who attended the sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, told state-run TV Perú that Europeans "killed each other in World War II" and other conflicts, "but now they are practically one country".
In this sense, he defended the project of creating South American citizenship, which is supported by the member countries of Unasur.
"We need to achieve the free movement of citizens and workers within any South American country, which is already taking place between the members of the Andean Community, but there are still areas of backwardness that want to take us back to the past", he said.
Among other things, the Ecuadorian president said he agreed to the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OAS) on the condition that the influence of Anglo-Saxon states be reduced and that the signatories of the San José Covenant on Human Rights be taken into account.
"Those in charge never commit to anything, and we South Americans sign everything.
It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is funded in Washington by the United States", he said, referring to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
President Correa confirmed that he did not regret the decision, because it did not betray his principles and respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He added that at the time, 'there was a reasonable suspicion that Assange could be extradited to a third country regardless of the ongoing trial'.
In addition, he criticized the Swedish judiciary for asking him to be interrogated on Swedish territory for an alleged sexual offence, whereas 'Sweden's own legislation allows for the interrogation to be conducted by videoconference call, which could be conducted from the Ecuadorian Embassy in London'.
Correa stated that there was a risk of Assange's physical and mental health deteriorating.
"I have not spoken to him since he has been in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he has a minor lung problem, but nothing serious", the Ecuadorian head of state said.
"But his physical and mental health are in danger of deteriorating because he is confined to a small space with no access to fresh air.
It would affect everyone's health", he added.
President Correa noted that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian Embassy in London on the basis of a permit allowing him to travel to Ecuador is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European courts, and stressed that talks were under way with London to resolve the imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
"We don't negotiate on human rights, we don't use that word in this case, but there were constant talks.
The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European courts, as Assange's lawyer Baltazar Garzón is leading a series of proceedings before different European bodies", he said.
He said that "if Britain issues a pass tomorrow, it will all be over".
And if Sweden can question Mr Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as is allowed by the law there and has been done in other cases, tomorrow this problem will be solved".
Correa used the situation to present himself as a defender of press freedom, making it clear that he would not tolerate "subversion, bad intentions and lies that undermine freedom of expression".
The biggest enemies of a free press are not us, the mean and depraved politicians, but bad journalists in the service of profit, pressure and blackmail", he said.
In this regard, he expressed joy that neither such journalists, "nor bankers, nor hegemonic countries, nor bourgeoisie rule Ecuador", and predicted that if re-elected, "he will continue to carry out changes in the right way and in the right direction".
President Correa also supported the decision to continue maintaining Paraguay's veto on UNASUR membership at least until its next election, arguing that the whole "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and coup d'état disguised as legality" because in fact "it has destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
The Ecuadorian president also said that he considered "absolutely appropriate" the wish of his Colombian counterpart Juan Manuel Santos to negotiate with Nicaragua on the maritime boundaries between the two countries now, in the wake of the International Court of Justice ruling in favor of Nicaragua.
The verdict is not currently admissible.
"It's a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to walk together.
They need to be assessed broadly to overcome them and to be able to move forward".
He also expressed hope that the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile would be settled in the same court, and expressed the view that "it is right for Latin America to seek international jurisdiction if both countries commit to accepting the judgment, however harsh".
Regarding the possibility of running for a third term in the upcoming presidential election in Ecuador, he noted that he views the possibility "with great optimism and joy, even if it is sometimes very difficult".
Correa has stated that if he loses the February 2013 election, he will retire from public life.
"I have never personally been interested in power, but unjust situations like the socioeconomic poverty in Ecuador can only be corrected by political power.
My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this probable victory, so we have to accept this responsibility", he said.
"If I win, it will be my last presidential term and then I will retire from politics.
If we lose, I'll lose the same.
I've made my decision", he said.
Correa also mentioned the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez in Cuba.
"I just spoke to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolas Maduro, who says that President Chávez has left for a scheduled routine medical treatment and his return to Cuba was expected after the campaign ended.
It is not a relapse in the president's health", he explained.
The Head of State of Ecuador today attended the sixth summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which concluded with calls for greater regional integration to maintain development, equality and security.
AIDS victims today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 when his test result was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was like being struck by lightning", he recalls, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor tried to "soften up a little bit", but apparently without success.
The boy kept it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on himself and started to educate himself about it, and he did so with such dedication that he celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the longest-serving patients in the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he joined in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since he was 22, which was unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, few treatment options and more stigma.
At the time, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him "because he had a cut".
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it's possible to live with this syndrome and live fully.
However, many people do not know they are sick and only come when the virus has destroyed their body and weakened their immune system, and then they fall victim to accidental infections.
Thirty-one years after the AIDS epidemic began, or at least since the first documented cases, "it is a great achievement that the life expectancy of a patient who starts treatment on time and in an appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara, adding that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious diseases specialist Andrade Villanueva, who specializes in HIV/AIDS, explained that as of 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a death sentence but that the length of survival and full life depends on the degree of damage to the immune system of the patients diagnosed, with those who do not use drugs doing better: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years and those with 500 CD4 cells up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that a person diagnosed with HIV at age 25 can, according to this study, "live safely for up to 75 years if treated", the doctor explained in the interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of AIDS deaths has dropped from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (United Nations Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of AIDS patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 as of May this year, but since 2005, universal access to antiretroviral drugs has been ensured.
Why do people still die from the disease?
"I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it is at my hospital.
The problem is that patients come in at a very advanced stage because they don't know the status of the disease, which is late in the disease".
It adds the compelling figure: "Nine out of ten patients come with a co-infection, and the only way to increase overall mortality is to diagnose the disease early, so that screening is widely available to all who ask for it".
His proposal is in line with the specialists and officials of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco and directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to get tested in a private lab just because his friend did, and despite his young age, he already had AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer disease that is one of the common complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather deal with it three times a week", they say, but that's not my case.
The change has been for the better, I'm eating healthy, exercising, taking medication".
To this day, his parents only know that he had cancer.
"I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but responsibly, I take care of myself and the other person", says Fabrizio, who accepted the invitation to share his experience with the daily MILENIO JALISCO to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today on World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested. If they've taken the risk, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, that's better. And if they've been diagnosed, let them know that they can live like anyone else if they're responsible".
This message sums up the slogan of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms at the counter
There is a huge gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a journalist in Guadalajara who researches HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places that do this, "the condom distribution has really increased, from one or two condoms to hundreds of condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who don't have access to condoms", he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are teenagers.
"What do you want?" is a common question filled with irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy workers, and health-care workers that teens want to avoid, says a reporter.
He proposed to change this inefficient distribution, to make condoms not just on the counter, but in the 100 dispensers in public restrooms, in places where young people often go.
"It's not promoting promiscuity.
Nor is it "paying for beer and motel", as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if he would approve of distributing condoms in his district.
It is best to make condoms available to those who already have sex", he noted.
Key numbers in the state of Jalisco
There were 13 435 cases (12 158 cases of AIDS and 1 317 cases of HIV).
This makes it the fourth-largest state in Mexico in terms of new and confirmed AIDS cases and the 13th-largest in terms of HIV.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% are blood-borne and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that some 50,000 people may be living with HIV, with four to five people unaware of the disease for every one recorded.
The judgment upheld by the US Court of Appeal, which does not recognise the restructuring of Grupo Vitro's debt resulting from the bankruptcy in Mexico, sets an unfortunate precedent for any national company with branches in a neighbouring country and a solvency problem.
The restructuring procedures that are permitted by Mexican law do not seem to be applicable in the Land of the Stars and Stripes, despite international agreements.
The approval of a ruling issued on June 15th of last year by Judge Harlin Hall of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies practically without defense against the possibility of confiscation of their assets across the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door for the major Mexican glass manufacturer to appeal three irregularities to the United States Supreme Court.
It should be noted, first, that while the judge in this case claims that creditors are to be governed by United States insolvency law, the New Orleans-based Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals says that the main procedure is to set up bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
First, this would indicate a lack of knowledge of international procedural cooperation in the insolvency of multinational enterprises.
In essence, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created for this purpose, designating the American Law Institute as the arbitrator.
Second, the judgment states that without a vote by the branches from the internal corporate structure, where the debt of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognised, the required majority for the approval of the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, Mexican law allows for this possibility.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first to adopt this scheme.
There are half a dozen examples like Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose internal debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
Moreover, even after the branches' votes had been counted, the creditors who had sued Vitro in the United States, i.e. the 'vulture' funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
In the vote, it would be about 45 percent to 37.
The Court of Appeal disregards this.
On the other hand, the Court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the background of the severe economic crisis that has hit the United States.
Meanwhile, the family firm of González Sady will appeal the re-examination directly to the Court of Appeal, so that the review will be conducted with full participation, that is, with the participation of five judges, because originally only three voted.
If he fails here, he will seek a review of the case at a higher level, in this case the United States Supreme Court.
The Court of First Instance, in its judgment of 12 December 2012, found that the Commission had failed to fulfil its obligations under the United States Bankruptcy Code by failing to adopt the necessary measures to comply with the requirements of the United States Bankruptcy Code.
It also points out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules for international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
A blow to both sides: punishment for Vitro and the state.
The overall assessment
For months, the Mexican aviation unions had been lying on the table with a criminal complaint against former Gaston Azcárraga Andrade, a former owner of the company, who was accused of fraud, and the union says the tank had already overflowed.
A court led by Carlos Díaz Chávez Morineau has just filed a lawsuit against the National Banking Commission and the Securities Commission, accusing them of obstruction of justice.
According to the Commission, the Office of the Auditor General systematically refused to report to the Prosecutor General of the Republic on the transaction carried out by this entrepreneur, in which he collected 198 million pesos from the IXE bank of Fideicomiso F/589 on behalf of Mexican Airlines.
The funds were most likely directed to the purchase of shares in the Hotel Professional Administration (Administradora Profesional de Hoteles).
As is known, Azcárraga Andrade is the majority shareholder of the Posadas hotel chain.
The Siege of Dragon Mar
A group of local and foreign environmentalists, academics, businessmen and ordinary citizens met at the Universidad de Caribe campus over the weekend to approve the creation of an association to prevent the opening of China's Dragon Mart in Cancun.
We are talking, as you know, about a huge commercial and distribution center with products from the "land of the great wall" targeting Mexico, Central America and the Caribbean, which would include a residential zone for employees of 150 companies at the bottom.
The Canacintra (Cámara Nacional de la Industria de Transformación) has already managed to unite the governors of the south-east zone to oppose a monumental site that would have partly devastated protected areas and that is the origin of all resistance to industry.
The ACTA document is over
The Senate's request, which the government did not consider, and which requested an explanation of the conditions and circumstances under which the Mexican ambassador to Japan signed the Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement, known in English by its acronym ACTA, has become outdated, according to the Mexican Institute of Industrial Property (Instituto Mexicano de la Propiedad Industrial).
As you know, this happened despite the fact that the Senate itself ruled out the possibility of considering it a threat to freedom of expression on social networks.
Homex in the long term
In an effort to pay off long-term debts and not affect short-term ones, Homex, a developer, is putting 500 million pesos worth of investment certificates on the market.
This series is the first of four identical ones that offer interest repayments every 28 days.
Competitive is born
The merger of leading IT companies such as NYCE, e-Quality and Kernet has created an association with the trade name Competival, which will target the software services market in Central and South America.
The investment in the business will exceed $1.5 billion.
Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
World champion basketball player Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been involved in the sport for more than 60 years, traveling the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of their local basketball as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Reyes was a fixture in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior player, a National Basketball League player, owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayamón of the National Basketball League, or president of the Puerto Rican Basketball Federation.
"I have held many positions in my life in basketball, including several simultaneously, such as being president of the National Basketball League (BSN) in the 1990s, general manager of the national team and president of the federation", Reyes recalled when visiting reporters at the Primera Hora newspaper at his home in Bayamon, where he has lived for more than 50 years with Isabel, his faithful wife.
"Basketball was my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his house, almost all of which are decorated with photos and memorabilia from his long career, testify to this.
Bayamon in the heart
With the greatest of all movements, he guards those that recall his tenure with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or owner of the team.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most, because I had the opportunity to play with the Los Vaqueros since 1967 and win eight championships, either as owner, co-owner, or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held between 1971 and 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship-- in 1981, when Jerome Mincy debuted on BSN.
"The team was then taken over by 'Cuco' Ortiz, who was an excellent leader", Reyes said.
"I remember Gene Bartow, who was the former coach here at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, said to me, 'I have a six-foot-tall player for you.
You want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended quarterback Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy brought Bayamon a championship win, then Gausse would contribute to the next one".
Gausse enjoyed the championship while playing for the Los Vaqueros, but only remotely, as he was already acting president of the basketball federation in 1988.
At the time, he wanted to focus on his duties and enjoy Mincy's place on the national team.
"I remember the first time we beat the United States in the Olympic qualifiers in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, but we should have won bronze if it wasn't for the Canadian referee who let us repeat the final toss", Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
He's among the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the national team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and beat the United States team, which was pretty similar to the one that took us bronze at the World Championships.
This team not only had Mincy, Gausse, Ramón Rivas, Fica López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also had youngsters (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, Leon brothers (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be in the team in 1990 due to a knee injury.
The team that may not have had the perfect lineup but was able to win the gold medal and bring us great joy was the 1995 Olympic qualifying team in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players on the roster like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner, who replaced players eliminated by a brawl at the Mar de Plata Pan American Games, we won gold against all odds.
What was Puerto Rico's best player?
It was without a doubt Piculin Ortiz.
His numbers in international tournaments are impressive.
No one from Puerto Rico has achieved the results of Piculin at this level.
Not to mention his involvement in the various leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican coach?
It's very difficult.
We had a very good generation, which included Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
I like Leo Arill's work very much.
What do you consider your greatest achievement in the Federation?
That I was part of the most glorious era of the national team from 1988 to 1995 and that in the early '90s, the National League of BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What didn't you get to prove?
There were things I wanted to introduce, like the division of youth categories by region.
Like Ponce boys playing only in their area and only competing against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Kids travel a lot now and play too many games, which isn't necessary.
I also see the benefit of compulsory certificates and courses for coaches, assistant referees and referees.
I'm glad to hear it.
What are you doing now?
I mostly listen to music, watch YouTube videos of music from my time, enjoy my grandchildren, and occasionally go to basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Fort Worth, Texas, became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R". on the television series Dallas, in which he played a man who acted recklessly and was sly and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new series Dallas, died Friday afternoon from complications related to cancer, according to an official family statement provided to The Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros.
"Larry has returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas to reprise the iconic role he loved most", his family said.
Larry's family and his closest friends were in Dallas with him for Thanksgiving.
"Linda Gray, who played Hagman's wife in both the original and new series, was with Hagman at the time of his death in a Dallas hospital", her agent Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
"He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented, and I will miss him terribly.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest", said Linda Gray in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992, and he himself admitted to drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver, and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before Dallas aired, Hagman made his name on television as the good guy in the light-hearted comedy I Dream of Jeannie, which ran on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (a genie) played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to his home to live with.
He also starred in two short-lived sitcoms, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His film appearances included critically acclaimed roles in The Group, Harry and Tonto and Primary Colors.
But it was Hangman's masterful performance in the form of the incredibly repulsive J.R. that brought him to the top of the stars.
A CBS drama series about the Ewings and other figures around them aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan "Who shot Jair?" was intended to create anticipation for an emotional piece where the Hangman character is nearly murdered, and not only caused a huge amount of speculation from viewers around the world, but also risked millions of dollars at the box office.
That also helped the show to break the record for viewership.
The November 1980 episode, which revealed the answer, averaged 41 million television viewers, making Dallas the second most-watched entertainment program in history after MASH, which ended its run in 1983 with 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin got pregnant with J.R. and he threatened to call her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had a reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, a greedy greedy man with a charismatic smile: a cunning businessman and unfaithful husband who tried to get his wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), who was an alcoholic, committed to a mental institution.
"I know what I want J.R. to have on his tombstone", Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, "Here lies the honorary citizen J.R. Ewing".
