Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew that the temptation was insurmountable: The end of the "long count" of the Mayan calendar, which was to come on December 21, was taken by many as proof that the end of the world was coming.
But Charmé had no idea what lay ahead in the months to come: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a budget deficit that some call "debt Armageddon", and the escalating conflict engulfing Israel, the place where, according to doomsday theorists, the Apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever", Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
